# Privacy-Preserving Record Linkage (PPRL) — COMP3850 Group 52

Industry capstone for Dinusha Vatsalan & Piyumi Seneviratne, Macquarie University.
Comparison of five record-linkage models under Bloom-filter encoding and differential privacy.

## Overview
Encodes quasi-identifiers into Bloom filters / Counting Bloom Filters (q-grams), applies
bit-level differential privacy (bit-flipping) at epsilon ∈ {2, 3, 4}, blocks records, and
classifies pairs as match / non-match using five models: threshold baseline, Logistic
Regression, Random Forest, SVM and KNN. Evaluated with F1, precision and recall.

## Repository structure
- `PPRL.ipynb` — main pipeline: encoding, differential privacy, blocking, models, evaluation
- `report/` — final report (key takeaways + analysis)
- `requirements.txt` — dependencies
- `README.md`

## Requirements
- Python 3.8+
- scikit-learn, numpy, pandas, bitarray (plus any others the notebook imports)
- Install with: `pip install -r requirements.txt`

## How to run
1. Install dependencies (above).
2. Place the sponsor-provided Alice and Bob files in `/data` (see Reproducing our results).
3. Open `PPRL.ipynb` in Jupyter and Run All.
4. Per-model F1, precision and recall print in the notebook output for each configuration.

## Reproducing our results
The Alice and Bob datasets are not included in this repo (provided by the sponsor).
To reproduce our experiments:
1. Place the sponsor-provided Alice and Bob files in `/data`.
2. Open `PPRL.ipynb`. Each experiment was run manually: set the epsilon value (2, 3 or 4)
   and select the Alice/Bob file near the top of the notebook, then Run All.
3. Blocking configurations tested: [2], [4] and [2,4].
4. The pipeline encodes the quasi-identifiers into Bloom filters (and Counting Bloom
   Filters), applies differential privacy by bit-flipping at the chosen epsilon, blocks
   records, then classifies each record pair as match / non-match using the five models
   (threshold baseline, Logistic Regression, Random Forest, SVM, KNN).
5. F1, precision and recall are recorded per model for each dataset × epsilon × blocking
   combination, and compiled into our results sheet and final report.
6. Each configuration was run once per setting.

## Key results
- ML models (especially SVM and Random Forest) were more resilient to DP noise and data
  corruption than the threshold baseline.
- Best model: SVM (~0.97 F1). Recommended epsilon 3–4 and Counting Bloom Filter encoding.

